Learn more and check in on the next two #IndianChiefCustoms through the link in our bio.

Learn more about the new Indian Chief through the link in our bio.

node.text:
For Perry Sands, his passion for customization, and in turn, the creation of the legendary Performance Machine Inc., began with the #IndianChief.

Today, his son @rolandsands carries the torch in many ways. With his own custom performance shop, @rolandsandsdesign, they now work to bring back a very special piece of the family's history.

Perry's story sets the stage for the new 2022 Indian Chief, as within its DNA is a bare-bones platform waiting for those with the will to do so, to tear it down and build it up again.

Catch Part 2 here later today or right now on our YouTube channel.

#indianmotorcycle

Introducing the @paulcoxindustries and @keinocycles custom #IndianChief built for hyper-realism tattooing royalty, @nikkohurtado. The first of three builds to be revealed as part of the #IndianChiefCustoms program.

"Late last year, Indian Motorcycle approached me about building a custom version of their upcoming 2022 #IndianChief, along with my old partner, Keino Sasaki. With the world still in the middle of pandemic lockdowns, it seemed crazy that this company was looking ahead to the future, and had total faith in things turning around. Fortunately, I’ve stayed busy all these years, through life's ups and downs, and appreciated the fact that Indian Motorcycle had confidence in the industry’s future, and in my work as well. I talked with them a bit more, and when I finally saw the new 2022 model, it seemed perfect for chopping, so I said “yes".
 
The project started off as a stock 2022 Indian Chief, which had sort of a bobbed, 50’s look to it. It was a little bit retro, but with modern touches that would make a cool version of an early chopper. It already had an aggressive stance, with shallow rake for maneuverability, so I built one of my Girdraulic front ends to fit it, and added a steering damper for high speed stability. I painted the bike, including Keino's hand made gas tank, in my custom Soylent Green metal flake, and hand tooled a leather saddle for the bike. The shifting was converted to Jockey, with a foot clutch, and the black rimmed wheels are now running Avon rubber. To get a lower look at the rear, we ran a swing arm mounted, heavy gauge fender from Led Sled that hugged the Avon 180mm perfectly. I had an old Indian Motorcycle front fender light that worked great as a tail light with a new red head lens. To keep that aggressive feel up front, we deleted the levers, mounted the hand controls on a custom Drag bar, and set them up on Bare Knuckle Performance 6” risers. Perfect fit." - Paul Cox

Learn more about this bike and our upcoming builds through the link in our bio.

Photos by @michaellichterphotography
